HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% of new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of people with HIV and AIDS.
Over 820,000 people are affected by these diseases, according to health authorities.
About 40,000 new cases have been reported already in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of the new cases are due to sexual transmission, which marks a change from the past.
In some regions of China, HIV has spread in the past as a result of blood transfusions.
But the number of people who have contracted HIV in this way has declined to almost zero, according to the Chinese health authorities during a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people affected by HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 units.
Sexual transmission of HIV is an urgent problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was criminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is still widespread.
Because of the country's traditional values, some studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men eventually marry women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are caused by inadequate protection during sexual relations within such relationships.
In 2003, the Chinese government promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs as part of its commitment to managing the problem.
