Update on the Red Sea: the concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The last report of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in the concentration of red tides in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of flowering in pine trees, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier.
The flowering of the red tide extends for about 130 miles north of the county of Pinellas south of the county of Lee.
The quays are about 10 miles away from Hillsborough County, but in less areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in the Easter County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in the county of Pinellas or away from its coasts, a low concentration off the county of Hillsborough, from a background concentration to a high concentration in the county of Manatee, from a background concentration to a high concentration in the county of Sarasota or away from its coasts, from a background concentration to a medium concentration in the county of Charlotte, from a background concentration to a high concentration in the county of Lee or away from its coasts and a low concentration in the county of Collier.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
While last week no case was reported in northwestern Florida.
